D. DNS Configuration
System A can reach System B with IP's and both are in same network.
If system B is considered as DB as domain name. Instead of pinging with IP, we can go with Names.
# add system b's IP in the system a


System A pings System B with the domain name DB and it fails to connect.
# if system A pings System B with DB, then it fails because need to add System A with domain name & IP from Domain server.

Also we can create a new DNS server which has all name resolution info. 

Note: If system A had all name resolution details with him but when IP's changes to the server we can't add it manually and monitor. 
It is applicable for all the systems.

Here DNS server comes in the picture and has all name resolution info with it.

From the system in the linux host server:
Now for every ping first it checks with etc/dns-config.file and checks DNS server.
The order might change based on the configuration.

www.google.com

www.google.com / maps.google.com - subdomain
google.com - domain
.com - top level domain


If system pings www.google.com
system doesn't know about the DNS name, it start looking for the IP from home router or dns server.

DNS server start looking for .com from root DNS server
And it will look for google.com from top level domain server
& start looking for www.google.com google dns server
& finally dns server replies the IP for www.google.com

